{
  "text": "Methylation of the p16/INK4a gene was observed in 60% of MALT lymphomas; however, p16 gene methylation status did not correlate with the presence of API2-MALT1 fusion or any other clinicopathological factor, suggesting that aberrant methylation of the p16 gene might be an early event in MALT lymphomagenesis. [CITATION_1] Examination of the methylation profiles of eight CpG islands, namely p15, p16, p73, hMLH1, DAPK, MINT1, MINT2, and MINT31, revealed that more than four genes were methylated in H. pylori-dependent MALT lymphomas while fewer than two genes were methylated in non-H. pylori-dependent cases, indicating that the pathogenesis of gastric MALT lymphomas, including the aberrant DNA methylation pattern, may differ between H. pylori-dependent and non-H. pylori-dependent cases. [CITATION_2] Aberrant DNA methylation thus plays critical roles in the pathogenesis of gastric MALT lymphomas, and determination of the DNA methylation pattern may hold promise as a clinical tool for surveillance of gastric MALT lymphomas.",
